# Button Controlled LED using Internal Pull-Up Resistor

This project demonstrates how to control an LED using a push button with Arduino's **internal pull-up resistor**.

## Project Description

Instead of using an external pull-up resistor, Arduino's built-in **INPUT_PULLUP** mode is enabled. In this configuration:

* The button pin normally reads **HIGH**.
* When the button is pressed, it connects the pin to **GND**, causing it to read **LOW**.
* The program uses an **if-else** statement to determine whether the LED should be turned on or off.


## Logic

* Button Released вЖТ Input = HIGH вЖТ LED OFF
* Button Pressed вЖТ Input = LOW вЖТ LED ON

## Learning Objectives

* Using `INPUT_PULLUP`
* Reading digital inputs
* Using `if-else` statements
* Controlling digital outputs

/*
==================================================
Project Name : Button Controlled LED
Author       : H√Љseyin ERDEM
Board        : Arduino UNO

Description:
This project demonstrates how to use the
Arduino internal pull-up resistor.

When the button is pressed:
    LED turns ON.

When the button is released:
    LED turns OFF.

The project uses an if-else statement
to control the LED.
==================================================
*/

// Pin connected to the push button
const int buttonPin = 2;

// Pin connected to the LED
const int ledPin = 13;

// Variable to store button state
int buttonState = HIGH;

void setup()
{
    // Configure the button pin using the internal pull-up resistor
    pinMode(buttonPin, INPUT_PULLUP);

    // Configure the LED pin as an output
    pinMode(ledPin, OUTPUT);
}

void loop()
{
    // Read the current state of the button
    buttonState = digitalRead(buttonPin);

    // If the button is pressed (LOW)
    if (buttonState == LOW)
    {
        // Turn the LED ON
        digitalWrite(ledPin, HIGH);
    }
    else
    {
        // Otherwise, turn the LED OFF
        digitalWrite(ledPin, LOW);
    }
}

